==English==

===Etymology===
From both the {{etyl|ML.|lang=en}} {{term|academicus|acadēmicus|lang=la}} and the {{etyl|fr|en}} {{term|académique|lang=fr}}; compare {{term|academy|lang=en}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/ˌækəˈdɛmɪk/}}, {{SAMPA|/%{k@"dEmIk/}}
* {{audio|En-us-academic.ogg|Audio (US)}}
*: {{rhymes|ɛmɪk}}

===Adjective===
{{en-adj}}

# Belonging to an [[academy]] or other higher institution of learning.
#* '''academic''' courses - [[w:William Warburton|William Warburton]]
#* '''academical''' study - [[w:George Berkeley|George Berkeley]]
# Belonging to the school or philosophy of [[Plato]]; as, the '''academic''' sect or philosophy.
# Being [[scholarly]]; literary or [[classical]], in distinction from [[scientific]].
# Conforming to set [[rule]]s and [[tradition]]s.
# Having an [[aptitude]] for [[study]].
# {{pejorative}} Having no practical importance.

